Circle|Circle of Eighteen	A cabal of powerful sorcerers who led the Rebel armies against the Lady's Empire. Drawn largely from the Empire's eastern borderlands, it organized major campaigns across the northern continent. Prominent members included Raker, Whisper, and Harden, and the Circle devoted considerable resources to finding the prophesied reincarnation of the White Rose.
Eye	An advanced sorcery employed by the Lady, used as a tool of interrogation across her Empire. It manifests as a gigantic yellow eyeball growing out from the Lady's face, surrounded by an all-encompassing lemon-colored glow and accompanied by an unsettling humming sound. The Eye compels truth from any subject: it cannot be deceived, can surface forgotten or unconsciously suppressed information, and is applied to Rebel prisoners and Imperial functionaries alike — all the way up to the Ten Who Were Taken, none of whom are exempt. Being examined by the Eye is universally described in the Annals as a harrowing experience; some individuals subjected to the "deep probe" come out listless and never recover. Despite its fearsome reputation, the Eye is not omniscient: the Lady must approach it with specific questions and familiarity with the subject, and it does not permit outright mind-reading — it only ensures the subject cannot lie.
Forvalaka	Supernatural predators from the equatorial jungles of D'loc Aloc, commonly called wereleopards. They appear human by day and become black leopards by night, hunting people for blood and organs. Their speed makes ordinary weapons nearly useless, while only sorcerers of great magnitude can harm them reliably with magic.
Pastel Wars	A series of major conflicts near the Second Cataract of the southern continent's great river, about two hundred years before The Black Company. Cho'n Delor, ruled by the Paingod and defended by the Black Company, fought the Triplet Cities. The Triplet Cities prevailed, but both sides were reduced to ruins and the region became scarred and haunted. The wars were remembered for pastel ribbons of battlefield sorcery and for the loss of four successive Annalists and the early Annals.
Rebel	The collective term for forces opposing the Lady's Empire on the northern continent, led chiefly by the powerful sorcerers of the Circle of Eighteen. Their cause drew strength from prophecies concerning the Great Comet and the return of the White Rose. They fought sustained campaigns against Imperial armies, the Ten Who Were Taken, and mercenaries including the Black Company.
TelleKurre|KurreTelle	The name of both a language and its native people, once the primary tongue and ruling ethnic group of the Domination. Under the Dominator's reign, the TelleKurre were elevated far above all other groups in his empire. The language was rendered extinct following the White Rose Rebellion, when TelleKurre cities were burned and their populations scattered. A regional vulgate called UchiTelle was also spoken. The spelling of TelleKurre names was notoriously free-form, with various letter combinations representing identical sounds.
Ten Who Were Taken|Taken	Ten notorious sorcerers of very high magnitude enslaved by the Dominator about five centuries before The Black Company. They served as his generals during the Domination and were later imprisoned with him and the Lady in the Barrowland. Their translated TelleKurre names include Soulcatcher, the Limper, the Howler, Shapeshifter, Stormbringer, the Hanged Man, Bonegnasher, Nightcrawler, Moonbiter, and the Faceless Man.
Tonk	A card game so central to the culture of the Black Company that Croaker described it as a tradition that "began ages before my time" and would "persist long after I am gone." Wherever the Company halts for even fifteen minutes, a tonk game tends to develop. Croaker characterized it as "one of the simplest games ever invented, rules-wise," but noted that the table talk accompanying play is as essential as the cards themselves. Small stakes were common, and banter between players was expected. The wizard One-Eye was infamously poor at the game unless he was cheating, and was known to squander considerable sums as a result.
